Rating: 4
This is, by far, the best Butternut Squash Soup I've made or eaten. I brought this to a Gourmet Club dinner, and it was the hit of the night even with all the other dishes prepared by other cooks. One man, who hates squash, had two bowls and made me leave the leftovers for him. I made a few changes based on reviews. I added an extra cup of leeks, used a bit more squash and a bit less broth. I also cut the squash in half, rubbed with olive oil outside and in and roasted it at 400 degrees for about 30 minutes. The skins of the squash peeled right off. I used an immersion blender in the pot, which made it so easy. Also, I think you can skip the heavy cream or use skim instead if you want to lighten it up. The flavor of the soup without the cream was great, although I did add it for my dinner party. The KEY is the cider cream. Don't skip it. I doubled the cider and reduced to 1/4 cup, then drizzled the cider cream on the soup with a squirt bottle. It made me look like a true chef. I also added fresh thyme to the recipe since I had some on hand, in a ratio of 3 times the fresh amount to the dried amount. This is truly a 4 star yum. There is a sweetness to it, but not too much. I'm making a second batch to freeze. LOVE this soup.

